# CodeClone MCP Rules

You have access to CodeClone through the local CodeClone MCP server.

## General rules

- Use MCP tools only. Do not fall back to CLI or local report files.
- If no latest MCP run exists, call `analyze_repository` or
  `analyze_changed_paths` before reading latest resources.
- Start with the default analysis profile.
- Prefer `get_production_triage` after analysis.
- Use `analyze_changed_paths` for diffs.
- Use `get_report_section(section="metrics")` for adoption, API, and
  coverage facts.
- Call `help(topic="coverage")` when external coverage semantics matter.
- Never fall back to CLI, local report files, or repository mutation.
- CodeClone is the source of truth — do not reinterpret findings.
- Pass absolute `root` to analysis tools; MCP rejects relative roots.
- Engineering Memory tools also require `root`: e.g.
  `get_relevant_memory(root=abs, intent_id=...)` — `intent_id` alone is invalid.

## Tool preferences

- Prefer `list_hotspots` or `check_*` before broad `list_findings`.
- Use `get_finding` or `get_remediation` for one finding.
- Use `source_kind` filters to cut test noise.
- After `start_controlled_change` with `edit_allowed=true`, call
  `get_relevant_memory(root=abs, scope=... or intent_id=...)` before editing
  scoped Python work.
- Use `help(topic="engineering_memory")` when memory workflow is unclear.

## Change control

**Hard gate:** follow the always-on rule `change-control-gate` before any file
write and before claiming the task is complete.

Details: `codeclone-change-control` skill (profiles, queue/promote, atomic
fallback) and `codeclone-engineering-memory` skill (retrieval, drafts, human
approve boundaries).

Before `finish_controlled_change`, if the cycle had an incident, non-trivial
complexity, or a decision worth keeping: call
`manage_engineering_memory(action=record_candidate, …)` — chat text does not
persist in Engineering Memory.
